Sure, here's a basic framework for a weather app in javascript:

HTML Structure:
- A form with an input field where the user can enter a location
- A button to trigger the search
- A container to hold the current temperature, description, and location

Javascript:
- Use an API to fetch weather data based on the user's input
- After receiving the data, parse it and extract the relevant information (temperature, description, location)
- Update the UI with the retrieved information

Here's a step-by-step guide on how you can build a simple weather app:

1. Create an HTML file with a form, an input field, and a container/div to hold the temperature, description, and location. 

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Weather App</title>
  </head>

  <body>
    <form>
      <input type="text" name="location" placeholder="Enter location">
      <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>  

    <div id="weather-info">
      <h2>Current weather in <span id="location"></span></h2>
      <h3><span id="temperature"></span> &#8451;</h3>
      <p id="description"></p>
    </div>

    <script src="app.js"></script>
  </body>

</html>
```

2. In the javascript file, select the form element and add an event listener for a submit event. 

```
const form = document.querySelector('form');

form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();

  // code to fetch and display weather data
});
```

3. Use an API (such as OpenWeatherMap or Weatherstack) to fetch weather data based on the user’s input. 

```
const API_KEY = 'your_api_key';
const form = document.querySelector('form');

form.addEventListener('submit', async (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();

  const location = form.elements.location.value;

  const response = await fetch(`https://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5/weather?q=${location}&units=metric&appid=${API_KEY}`);
});
```

4. Parse the retrived data, and extract the temperature, description and location.


```
const API_KEY = 'your_api_key';
const form = document.querySelector('form');
const temperatureElement = document.getElementById('temperature');
const descriptionElement = document.getElementById('description');
const locationElement = document.getElementById('location');

form.addEventListener('submit', async (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();

  const location = form.elements.location.value;

  const response = await fetch(`https://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5/weather?q=${location}&units=metric&appid=${API_KEY}`);
  const data = await response.json();

  const temperature = data.main.temp;
  const description = data.weather[0].description;
  const locationName = data.name;

  temperatureElement.textContent = temperature;
  descriptionElement.textContent = description;
  locationElement.textContent = locationName;
});
```

5. Update the UI by adding the extracted temperature, description and location to their respective HTML elements.

```
const temperatureElement = document.getElementById('temperature');
const descriptionElement = document.getElementById('description');
const locationElement = document.getElementById('location');

temperatureElement.textContent = temperature;
descriptionElement.textContent = description;
locationElement.textContent = locationName;
```

And that's it! You can add some additional styling or features to make it more visually appealing or functional.

Sure! Here's a cheat sheet with some important JavaScript concepts and syntax:

1. Variables:
```
// Declare a variable
let x;

// Declare and initialize a variable
let name = "John";

// Constant variable
const PI = 3.14159;

// Reassign variable value
x = 5;
name = "Jane";
```

2. Data Types:
```
// String
let name = "John";

// Number
let age = 30;

// Boolean
let isStudent = true;

// Object
let person = { name: "John", age: 30 };

// Array
let fruits = ["apple", "banana", "orange"];
```

3. Functions:
```
// Function declaration
function sayHello(name) {
  console.log("Hello, " + name + "!");
}

// Function expression
const double = function(x) {
  return x * 2;
}

// Arrow function
const add = (x, y) => {
  return x + y;
}

// Function call
sayHello("John");

// Function return
let result = double(5);
```

4. Conditional Statements:
```
// if-else statement
if (age < 18) {
  console.log("Not legal age");
} else {
  console.log("Legal age");
}

// switch statement
let color = "red";
switch (color) {
  case "red":
    console.log("Red color");
    break;
  case "blue":
    console.log("Blue color");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Unknown color");
    break;
}
```

5. Loops:
```
// for loop
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
  console.log(i);
}

// while loop
let i = 0;
while (i < 10) {
  console.log(i);
  i++;
}

// do-while loop
let j = 0;
do {
  console.log(j);
  j++;
} while (j < 10);

// for-in loop (iterating over object properties)
let person = { name: "John", age: 30 };
for (let property in person) {
  console.log(property + ": " + person[property]);
}

// for-of loop (iterating over iterable object, like an array)
let fruits = ["apple", "banana", "orange"];
for (let fruit of fruits) {
  console.log(fruit);
}
```

This is just a brief overview of some important concepts in JavaScript. There's much more to discover, but this cheat sheet should help get you started!

Sure! Here's a basic to-do list application in JavaScript:

HTML Structure:
```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Todo List</title>
  </head>

  <body>
    <div id="todo-list">
      <h1>Todo List</h1>
      <form>
        <input type="text" id="todo-input" placeholder="Add new todo">
        <button type="submit" id="add-button">Add</button>
      </form>
      <ul id="todo-items"></ul>
    </div>

    <script src="app.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
```

JavaScript Code:
```
const form = document.querySelector('form');
const todoInput = document.getElementById('todo-input');
const todoList = document.getElementById('todo-items');
let todos = [];

function addTodo() {
  // create a new todo object and push it to the todos array
  const todo = {
    id: Date.now(),
    text: todoInput.value,
    done: false
  };
  todos.push(todo);

  // render the new todo item
  renderTodoItem(todo);

  // clear the input
  todoInput.value = '';
}

function removeTodoById(id) {
  todos = todos.filter((todo) => todo.id !== id);
  renderTodoList();
}

function toggleTodoById(id) {
  const todo = todos.find((todo) => todo.id === id);
  todo.done = !todo.done;
  renderTodoList();
}

function renderTodoItem(todo) {
  // create a new list item element for the todo
  const li = document.createElement('li');

  // add the todo text to the list item and set a data attribute for the id
  li.textContent = todo.text;
  li.dataset.id = todo.id;

  // add a button to toggle the todo's "done" status
  const toggleButton = document.createElement('button');
  toggleButton.textContent = 'Done';
  toggleButton.addEventListener('click', () => toggleTodoById(todo.id));
  li.appendChild(toggleButton);

  // add a button to remove the todo item
  const removeButton = document.createElement('button');
  removeButton.textContent = 'Remove';
  removeButton.addEventListener('click', () => removeTodoById(todo.id));
  li.appendChild(removeButton);

  // add the list item to the todo list element
  todoList.appendChild(li);
}

function renderTodoList() {
  // clear the todo list before rendering the updated list
  todoList.innerHTML = '';

  // render each todo item in the todos array
  todos.forEach((todo) => renderTodoItem(todo));
}

form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  addTodo();
});

renderTodoList();
```

In the HTML structure, we create a form with an input field and add button to allow users to add new to-dos. We also add a list element to display the current to-do items.

In JavaScript, we declare variables for the form, input field, and list element, as well as an empty array to hold the to-dos. We then create several functions:

1. `addTodo`: this function creates a new to-do object with a unique id, text, and done status, and pushes it to the todos array. It then calls the `renderTodoItem` function to add the to-do to the list, and clears the input field.
2. `removeTodoById`: this function removes a to-do from the todos array and calls the `renderTodoList` function to update the display.
3. `toggleTodoById`: this function toggles the "done" status of a to-do and calls the `renderTodoList` function to update the display.
4. `renderTodoItem`: this function creates a new list item element with a toggle button, remove button, and the to-do text. It sets a data attribute for the to-do id and adds the element to the todo list.
5. `renderTodoList`: this function clears the todo list and renders each to-do item in the todos array.

Finally, we add an event listener to the form to call the `addTodo` function when the form is submitted, and we call the `renderTodoList` function to initialize the display.

And that's it! You now have a functional to-do list application in JavaScript. Feel free to customize it to fit your needs or add more advanced features like drag and drop or priority levels.
